        <para> The report found that projects completed by the largest American companies had on
            average only 42% of the originally-proposed features and functions. Smaller companies
            faired much better. A total of 78.4% of their software projects were deployed with at
            least 74.2% of their original features and functions. </para>
        <para> On average the content deficiencies across projects have been reduced over time.
            While in 1994 only 61% of the required features were delivered on challenged projects,
            the challenged projects in 2000 delivered 67% of the originally proposed features.
        </para>
    </section>

    <section>
        <title>Complete failures</title>
        <para> The Standish report found that in 1994 31.1% of projects got cancelled before
            completion. By 2003 the total failure rate has been reduced to 15% of all projects. </para>
        <para> Based on their research, The Standish Group estimated that in 1995 American companies
            and government agencies spent $81 billion for canceled software projects. </para>
    </section>

